<section xml:id="review-systems-of-linear-equations" permid="bFL">
  <title>Systems of Linear Equations Chapter Review</title>
  <subsection permid="HMU">
    <title>Solving Systems of Linear Equations by Graphing</title>
    <p permid="dnU">
      In <xref ref="section-solving-systems-of-linear-equations-by-graphing">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of system of linear equations and how <!-- They are packaged with a large left brace indicating that this is a collection of two distinct equations, not one equation that was somehow algebraically manipulated into an equivalent equation. A -->a solution to a system of linear equation is a point where the graphs of the two equations cross.
      We also considered <xref ref="list-summary-of-types-of-systems" text="custom">special systems</xref>
      of equations where the lines they define coincide or never cross.<!-- To denote the <term>solution set</term>, we write that point in set brackets. The first method we learned systems of linear equations was to <xref ref="section-solving-systems-of-linear-equations-by-graphing" text="custom">solve them by graphing</xref>. -->
    </p>

    <example permid="kZx">
      <title>Solving Systems of Linear Equations by Graphing</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="CVX">
          Solve the following system of equations by graphing:
          <me permid="VJv">
            \left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            y \amp {}={} \amp {-\frac{2}{3}x} \amp {}-{} \amp 4 \\
            y \amp {}={} \amp {-4x} \amp {}-{} \amp 14 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="cZz">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="xnP">

          <stack>
            <p permid="ndf">
              The first equation, <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x-4</m>,
              is a linear equation in <xref ref="definition-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>
              with a slope of <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> and a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,-4)</m>.
              The second equation, <m>y=-4x-14</m>,
              is a linear equation in slope-intercept form with a slope of <m>-4</m> and a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,-14)</m>.
              We'll use this information to graph both lines in <xref ref="figure-review-system-graphing">Figure</xref>.
            </p>

            <p permid="Tko">
              The two lines intersect where <m>x=-3</m> and <m>y=-2</m>,
              so the solution of the system of equations is the point <m>(-3,-2)</m>.
              We write the solution set as <m>\{(-3,-2)\}</m>.
            </p>
          </stack>

          <figure xml:id="figure-review-system-graphing" permid="zrx">
            <caption>Graphs of <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x-4</m> and <m>y=-4x-14</m>.</caption>
            <image permid="tgM">
              <description>A Cartesian grid with two intersecting lines; one line has a y-intercept of -4 and a slope of -2/3; the other line has a y-intercept of -14 and a slope of -4</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-9,xmax=1,
                            ymin=-16,ymax=2,
                            xtick={-8,-7,...,-1},
                            ytick={-14,-12,...,-2},
                            minor xtick={-9,-8,...,1},
                            minor ytick={-16,-14,...,2},
                            ]
                    \addplot[firstcurve]expression[domain=-9:1]{-2/3*x-4} node[pos=0.75,sloped,above] {$y=-\frac{2}{3}x-4$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve]expression[domain=-4:.5]{-4*x-14} node[pos=0.5,sloped,below] {$y=-4x-14$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,-4) (-6,0)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,-14) (-1,-10) (-2,-6)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-3,-2)} node[below left] {$(-3,-2)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="RgG">
      <title>Special Systems of Equations</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="jdg">
          Solve the following system of equations by graphing:
          <me permid="BQE">
            \left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{2}
            y \amp {}={} \frac{3}{2}(x-1)+4 \\
            3x-2y \amp {}={} 4 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="JgI">
        <p permid="fyG">
          The first equation, <m>y=\frac{3}{2}(x-1)+4</m>,
          is a linear equation in <xref ref="definition-point-slope-form" text="custom">point-slope form</xref>
          with a slope of <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> that passes through the point <m>(1,4)</m>.
          The second equation, <m>3x-2y=4</m>,
          is a linear equation in <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref> To graph this line,
          we either need to find the intercepts or put the equation into slope-intercept form.
          Just for practice, we will put the line in slope-intercept form.
          <md permid="hXN">
            <mrow>3x-2y\amp=4</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>3x\subtractright{3x}-2y\amp=\subtractright{3x}+4</mrow> -->
            <mrow>-2y\amp=-3x+4</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-2y}{-2}\amp=\divideunder{-3x}{-2}+\divideunder{4}{-2}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{3}{2}x-2</mrow>
          </md>
          We'll use this information to graph both lines:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="duY">
          <figure permid="rMY">
            <caption>Graphs of <m>y=\frac{3}{2}(x-1)+4</m> and <m>3x-2y=4</m>.</caption>
            <image permid="ZnV">
              <description>A Cartesian grid with two intersecting lines; one line has a y-intercept of -4 and a slope of -2/3; the other line has a y-intercept of -14 and a slope of -4</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[ymin=-6,ymax=8,
                            ytick={-5,-4,...,7},
                            minor ytick={-6,-5,...,8},
                            ]
                    \addplot[firstcurve]expression[domain=-5.666:3.666]{3/2*(x-1)+4} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above] {$y=\frac{3}{2}(x-1)+4$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve]expression[domain=-2.666:6.666]{3/2*x-2} node[pos=0.7,sloped,below] {$3x-2y=4$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(1,4) (3,7) (-1,1)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,-2) (2,1) (4,4)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

          <p permid="LFP">
            The two lines never intersect: they are parallel.
            So there are no solutions to the system of equations.
            We write the solution set as <m>\emptyset</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="nUd">
    <title>Substitution</title>
    <p permid="Jvd">
      In <xref ref="section-substitution">Section</xref>,
      we covered the substitution method of solving systems of equations.
      We isolated one variable in one equation and then substituted into the other equation to solve for one variable.
    </p>

    <example permid="JCh">
      <title>Solving Systems of Equations Using Substitution</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="Pkp">
          Solve this system of equations using substitution:
          <md permid="OeW">
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            -5x\amp {}+{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp -10 \\
            4x\amp {}-{} \amp 3y \amp {}={} \amp -1  \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="pnR">
        <p permid="XUh">
          We need to solve for <em>one</em>
          of the variables in <em>one</em> of our equations.
          Looking at both equations,
          it will be best to solve for <m>y</m> in the second equation.
          The coefficient of <m>y</m> in that equation is smallest.
          <md permid="umf">
            <mrow>4x-3y\amp=-1</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>4x-3y\subtractright{4x}\amp=-1\subtractright{4x}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>-3y\amp=-1-4x</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-3y}{-3}\amp=\divideunder{-1}{-3}-\divideunder{4x}{-3}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{3}x</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="BXI">
          <p permid="Ebq">
            Replace <m>\substitute{y}</m> in the first equation with <m>\substitute{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{3}x}</m>,
            giving us a linear equation in only one variable,
            <m>x</m>, that we may solve:
            <md permid="ato">
              <mrow>-5x+6\substitute{y}\amp=-10</mrow>
              <mrow>-5x+6\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{3}x}\right)\amp=-10</mrow>
              <mrow>-5x+2+8x\amp=-10</mrow>
              <mrow>3x+2\amp=-10</mrow>
              <!-- <mrow>3x+2\subtractright{2}\amp=-10\subtractright{2}</mrow> -->
              <mrow>3x\amp=-12</mrow>
              <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{3x}{3}\amp=\divideunder{-12}{3}</mrow> -->
              <mrow>x\amp=-4</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p permid="kiz">
            Now that we have the value for <m>x</m>,
            we need to find the value for <m>y</m>.
            We have already solved the second equation for <m>y</m>,
            so that is the easiest equation to use.
            <md permid="GAx">
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{3}\substitute{x}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{3}+\frac{4}{3}\left(\substitute{-4}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{3}-\frac{16}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{15}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-5</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="QpI">
          To check this solution, we replace
          <m>x</m> with <m>-4</m> and
          <m>y</m> with <m>-5</m> in each equation:
          <md permid="mHG">
            <mrow>-5x+6y \amp=-10  \amp  4x-3y \amp= -1</mrow>
            <mrow>-5(-4)+6(-5) \amp\wonder{=}-10  \amp  4(-4)-3(-4) \amp\wonder{=}-1</mrow>
            <mrow>20-30 \amp\confirm{=}-10  \amp  -16+15 \amp\confirm{=} -1</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="wwR">
          We conclude then that this system of equations is true when <m>x=-4</m> and <m>y=-5</m>.
          Our solution is the point <m>(-4,-5)</m> and we write the solution set as <m>\{(-4,-5)\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Solving Systems of Equations Using Substitution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Solve this system of equations using substitution:
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                4x\amp {}-{} \amp 3y \amp {}={} \amp -4 \\
                -2x\amp {}+{} \amp 9y \amp {}={} \amp 14 \\
                \end{alignedat}
              \right.
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We need to solve for <em>one</em> of the variables in <em>one</em> of our equations.
          Looking at both equations, it will be best to solve for <m>x</m> in the second equation.
          The coefficient of <m>x</m> in that equation is smallest.
          <md>
            <mrow>-2x+9y\amp=14</mrow>
            <mrow>-2x+9y\subtractright{9y}\amp=14\subtractright{9y}</mrow>
            <mrow>-2x\amp=14-9y</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-2x}{-2}\amp=\divideunder{14}{-2}-\divideunder{9y}{-2}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-7+\frac{9}{2}y</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Replace <m>\substitute{x}</m> in the first equation with <m>\substitute{-7+\frac{9}{2}y</m>,
          giving us a linear equation in only one variable, <m>y</m>, that we may solve:
          <md>
            <mrow>4x-3y\amp=-4</mrow>
            <mrow>4\left(\substitute{-7+\frac{9}{2}y}\right)-3y\amp=-4</mrow>
            <mrow>-28+18y-3y\amp=-4</mrow>
            <mrow>-28+15y\amp=-4</mrow>
            <mrow>-28+15y\addright{28}\amp=-4\addright{28}</mrow>
            <mrow>15y\amp=24</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{15y}{15}\amp=\divideunder{24}{15}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{8}{5}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Now that we have the value for <m>y</m>, we need to find the value for <m>x</m>.
          We have already solved the second equation for <m>x</m>, so that is the easiest equation to use.
          <md>
            <mrow>x\amp=-7+\frac{9}{2}y</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-7+\frac{9}{2}\substitute{\left(\frac{8}{5}\right)}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-7+\frac{72}{10}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{35}{5}+\frac{36}{5}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          To check this solution, we replace <m>\highlight{x}</m> with <m>\highlight{\frac{1}{5}}</m>
          and <m>\highlight[magenta]{y}</m> with <m>\highlight[magenta]{\frac{8}{5}}</m> in each equation:
          <md>
            <mrow>4\highlight{x}-3\highlight[magenta]{y} \amp=-4  \amp  -2\highlight{x}+9\highlight[magenta]{y} \amp= 14</mrow>
            <mrow>4\left(\highlight{\frac{1}{5}}\right)-3\left(\highlight[magenta]{\frac{8}{5}}\right) \amp\wonder{=}3  \amp  -2\left(\highlight{\frac{1}{5}}\right)+9\left(\highlight[magenta]{\frac{8}{5}}\right) \amp\wonder{=}14</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{4}{5}-\frac{24}{5}\amp\wonder{=}-4\amp -\frac{2}{5}+\frac{72}{5}\amp\wonder{=}14</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{-20}{5}\amp\wonder{=}-4\amp \frac{70}{5}\amp\wonder{=}14</mrow>
            <mrow>-4\amp\confirm{=}-4\amp 14\amp\confirm{=}14</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          We conclude then that this system of equations is true when <m>x=\frac{1}{5}</m> and <m>y=\frac{8}{5}</m>.
          Our solution is the point <m>\left(\frac{1}{5},\frac{8}{5}\right)</m> and we write the solution set as <m>\left\{\left(\frac{1}{5},\frac{8}{5}\right)\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example permid="pJq">
      <title>Applications of Systems of Equations</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="vry">
          The <url href="http://ruskranchnaturecenter.org">Rusk Ranch Nature Center</url><fn>
          <url href="http://ruskranchnaturecenter.org">ruskranchnaturecenter.org</url>
          </fn> in south-western Oregon is a volunteer run nonprofit that exists to promote the wellbeing of the local communities and conserve local nature with an emphasis on native butterflies.
          They sell admission tickets:
          <m>\$6</m> for adults and <m>\$4</m> for children.
          Amanda, who was working at the front desk,
          counted that one day she sold a total of <m>79</m> tickets and had <m>\$384</m> in the register from those ticket sales.
          She didn't bother to count how many were adult tickets and how many were child tickets because she knew she could use math to figure it out at the end of the day.
          So, how many of the <m>79</m> tickets were adult and how many were child?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Vva">
        <p permid="cEa">
          Let's let <m>a</m> represent the number of adult tickets sold and <m>c</m> represent the number of child tickets sold.
          We need to build two equations to solve a system for both variables.
        </p>

        <p permid="ILj">
          The first equation we will build relates to the fact that there were <m>79</m> total tickets sold.
          If we combine both the number of adult tickets and child tickets,
          the total is <m>79</m>.
          This fact becomes:
          <me permid="SOP">
            a+c=79
          </me>
        </p>

        <p permid="oSs">
          For the second equation we need to use the per-ticket dollar amounts to generate the total cost of <m>\$384</m>.
          The amount of money that was made from adult tickets is found my multiplying the number of adult tickets sold,
          <m>a</m>,
          by the price per ticket, <m>\$6</m>.
          Similarly, the amount of money from child tickets is found my multiplying the number of child tickets sold,
          <m>c</m>,
          by the price per ticket, <m>\$4</m>.
          These two amounts  will add to be <m>\$384</m>.
          This fact becomes:
          <me permid="yVY">
            6a+4c=384
          </me>
          And so, our system is
          <md permid="fdh">
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            a\amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 79 \\
            6a\amp {}+{} \amp 4c \amp {}={} \amp 384 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
          To solve, we will use the substitution method and solve the first equation for the variable <m>a</m>.
          <md permid="Lkq">
            <mrow>a+c\amp=79</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>a+c\subtractright{c}\amp=79\subtractright{c}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>a\amp=79-c</mrow>
          </md>
          Now we will substitute <m>\substitute{79-c}</m> for
          <m>\substitute{a}</m> in the second equation.
          <md permid="rrz">
            <mrow>6\substitute{a}+4c\amp=384</mrow>
            <mrow>6\left(\substitute{79-c}\right)+4c\amp=384</mrow>
            <mrow>474-6c+4c\amp=384</mrow>
            <mrow>474-2c\amp=384</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>474-2c\subtractright{474}\amp=384\subtractright{474}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>-2c\amp=-90</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{-2c}{-2}\amp=\divideunder{-90}{-2}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>c\amp=45</mrow>
          </md>
          Last, we will solve for <m>a</m> by substituting <m>\substitute{45}</m> in for
          <m>\substitute{c}</m> in the equation <m>a=79-c</m>.
          <md permid="XyI">
            <mrow>a\amp=79-c</mrow>
            <mrow>a\amp=79-\substitute{45}</mrow>
            <mrow>a\amp=34</mrow>
          </md>
          Our conclusion is that Amanda sold <m>34</m> adult tickets and <m>45</m> child tickets.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="VQz">
      <title>Solving Special Systems of Equations with Substitution</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="byH">
          Solve the systems of linear equations using substitution.

          <ol label="a." cols="2" permid="jyF">
            <li permid="vMX">
              <p permid="Rvb">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{1}
                3x-5y \amp {}={} 9 \\
                x\amp {}={} \frac{5}{3}y+3 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="bUg">
              <p permid="xCk">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{1}
                y+7\amp {}={} 4x \\
                2y-8x\amp {}={} 7 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="BCj">
        <p permid="UZB">
          To solve the systems using substitution,
          we first need to solve for one variable in one equation,
          then substitute into the <em>other</em> equation.

          <ol label="a." permid="Xkn">
            <li permid="Ibp">
              <p permid="dJt">
                In this case,
                <m>x</m> is already solved for in the second equation so we can substitute <m>\substitute{\frac{5}{3}y+3}</m> everywhere we see
                <m>\substitute{x}</m> in the first equation.
                Then simplify and solve for <m>y</m>.
                <md permid="DFR">
                  <mrow>3\substitute{x}-5y\amp=9</mrow>
                  <mrow>3\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{3}y+3}\right)-5y\amp=9</mrow>
                  <mrow>5y+9-5y\amp=9</mrow>
                  <mrow>9\amp=9</mrow>
                </md>
                We will stop here since we have eliminated all of the variables in the equation and ended with a
                <em>true</em> statement.
                Since <m>9</m> always equals <m>9</m>, no matter what,
                then any value of <m>y</m> must make the original equation,
                <m>3\left(\frac{5}{3}y+3\right)-5y=9</m> true.
                If you recall from the <xref ref="section-substitution" text="custom">section on substitution</xref>,
                this means that both lines <m>3x-5y=9</m> and
                <m>x=\frac{5}{3}y+3</m> are in fact the same line.
                Since a solution to a system of linear equations is any point where the lines touch,
                <em>all</em> points along both lines are solutions.
                We can say this in English as,
                <q>The solutions are all points on the line <m>3x-5y=9</m>,</q> or in math as,
                <q>The solution set is <m>\{(x,y)\mid 3x-5y=9\}</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="oiy">
              <p permid="JQC">
                We will first solve the top equation for <m>y</m>.
                <md permid="jNa">
                  <mrow>y+7\amp=4x</mrow>
                  <!-- <mrow>y+7\subtractright{7}\amp=4x\subtractright{7}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>y\amp=4x-7</mrow>
                </md>
                Now we can substitute <m>\substitute{4x-7}</m> wherever we see
                <m>\substitute{y}</m> in the second equation.
                <md permid="PUj">
                  <mrow>2\substitute{y}-8x\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>2\left(\substitute{4x-7}\right)-8x\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>8x-14-8x\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>-14\amp=7</mrow>
                </md>
                We will stop here since we have eliminated all of the variables in the equation and ended with a
                <em>false</em> statement.
                Since <m>-14</m> never equals <m>7</m>,
                then no values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> can make the original system true.
                If you recall from the <xref ref="section-substitution" text="custom">section on substitution</xref>,
                this means that the lines <m>y+7=4x</m> and <m>2y-8x=7</m> are parallel.
                Since a solution to a system of linear equations is any point where the lines touch,
                and parallel lines never touch,
                <em>no</em> points are solutions.
                We can say this in English as,
                <q>There are no solutions,</q> or in math as,
                <q>The solution set is <m>\emptyset</m>.</q>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="Ubm">
    <title>Elimination</title>
    <p permid="pCm">
      In <xref ref="section-elimination">Section</xref>,
      we explored a third way of solving systems of linear equations called elimination where we add two equations together to cancel a variable.
    </p>

    <example permid="ieR">
      <title>Solving Systems of Equations by Elimination</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="HFQ">
          Solve the system using elimination.
          <me permid="wbs">
            \left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            4x\amp {}-{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 13 \\
            5x\amp {}+{} \amp 4y \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="hJs">
        <p permid="BgK">
          To solve the system using elimination,
          we first need to scale one or both of the equations so that one variable has equal but opposite coefficients in the system.
          In this case,
          we will choose to make <m>y</m> have opposite coefficients because the signs are already opposite for that variable in the system.
        </p>

        <p permid="hnT">
          We need to multiply the first equation by <m>2</m> and the second equation by <m>3</m>.
          <md permid="ciB">
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            4x\amp {}-{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 13 \\
            5x\amp {}+{} \amp 4y \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            \multiplyleft{2}(4x\amp {}-{} \amp 6y) \amp {}={} \amp \multiplyleft{2}(13) \\
            \multiplyleft{3}(5x\amp {}+{} \amp 4y) \amp {}={} \amp \multiplyleft{3}(-1) \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            8x\amp {}-{} \amp 12y \amp {}={} \amp  26\\
            15x\amp {}+{} \amp 12y \amp {}={} \amp -3 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
          We now have an equivalent system of equations where the <m>y</m>-terms can be eliminated:
          <md permid="IpK">
            <mrow>\begin{aligned}
            8x-12y\\
            {}+15x+12y
            \end{aligned}
            \amp=
            \begin{aligned}
            26\\
            {}+(-3)
            \end{aligned}</mrow>
            <intertext>So we have:</intertext>
            <mrow>23x\amp=23</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{23x}{23}\amp=\divideunder{23}{23}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>x\amp=1</mrow>
          </md>
          To solve for <m>y</m>, we will substitute <m>\substitute{1}</m> for
          <m>\substitute{x}</m> into either of the original equations.
          We will use the first equation, <m>4x-6y=13</m>:
          <md permid="owT">
            <mrow>4\substitute{x}-6y\amp=13</mrow>
            <mrow>4(\substitute{1})-6y\amp=13</mrow>
            <mrow>4-6y\amp=13</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>4-6y\subtractright{4}\amp=13\subtractright{4}</mrow> -->
            <mrow>-6y\amp=9</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-6y}{-6}\amp=\divideunder{9}{-6}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
          </md>
          To verify this,
          we substitute the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> values into both of the original equations.
          <md permid="UEc">
            <mrow>4x-6y\amp=13\amp 5x+4y\amp=-1</mrow>
            <mrow>4(\substitute{1})-6\left(\substitute{-\frac{3}{2}}\right)\amp\wonder{=}13\amp 5(\substitute{1})+4\left(\substitute{-\frac{3}{2}}\right)\amp\wonder{=}-1</mrow>
            <mrow>4+9\amp\confirm{=}13\amp 5-6\amp\confirm{=}-1</mrow>
          </md>
          So the solution is the point
          <m>\left(-\frac{3}{2},1\right)</m> and the solution set is <m>\left\{\left(-\frac{3}{2},1\right)\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="Oma">
      <title>Solving Special Systems of Equations with Elimination</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="nMZ">
          Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
          <md permid="ALl">
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            24x \amp {}+{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 9 \\
            8x \amp {}+{} \amp 2y \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="NQB">
        <p permid="Nvc">
          To eliminate the <m>x</m>-terms,
          we will scale the second equation by <m>-3</m>.
          <md permid="gSu">
            <mrow>\amp\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            24x \amp {}+{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 9 \\
            \multiplyleft{-3}(8x\amp {}+{} \amp 2y) \amp {}={}\amp \multiplyleft{-3}(2) \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            24x \amp {}+{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 9 \\
            -24x \amp {}-{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp -6 \\
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="tCl">
          Adding the respective sides of the equation, we have:
          <me permid="MZD">
            0=3
          </me>
          Both of the variables have been eliminated.
          In this case, the statement <m>0=3</m> is just false,
          no matter what <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are.
          So the system has no solution.
          The solution set is <m>\emptyset</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="utj">
      <title>Deciding to Use Substitution versus Elimination</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="TUi">
          Decide which method would be easiest to solve the systems of linear equations:
          substitution or elimination.

          <ol label="a." cols="4" permid="PFO">
            <li permid="UpH">
              <p permid="pXL">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                2x \amp {}+{} \amp 3y \amp {}={} \amp -11 \\
                5x \amp {}-{} \amp 6y \amp {}={} \amp 13 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="AwQ">
              <p permid="WeU">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                x \amp {}-{} \amp 7y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                9x \amp {}-{} \amp 16y \amp {}={} \amp -4 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="gDZ">
              <p permid="Cmd">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                6x \amp {}+{} \amp 30y \amp {}={} \amp 15 \\
                4x \amp {}+{} \amp 20y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="MLi">
              <p permid="itm">
                <me>
                \left\{
                \begin{alignedat}{1}
                y\amp {}={} 3x {}-{} 2 \\
                y\amp {}={} 7x {}+{} 6 \\
                \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="tXK">
        <p permid="ZJu">
          <ol label="a." permid="Drw">
            <li permid="sSr">
              <p permid="OAv">
                Elimination is probably easiest here.
                Multiply the first equation by <m>2</m> and eliminate the <m>y</m> variables.
                The solution to this one is <m>(-1,-3)</m> if you want to solve it for practice.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="YZA">
              <p permid="uHE">
                Substitution is probably easiest here.
                Solve the first equation for <m>x</m> and substitute it into the second equation.
                We <em>could</em> use elimination if we multiplied the first equation by <m>-9</m> and eliminate the <m>x</m> variable,
                but it's probably a little more work than substitution.
                The solution to this one is <m>(-4,-2)</m> if you want to solve it for practice.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="FgJ">
              <p permid="aON">
                Elimination is probably easiest here.
                Multiply the first equation by <m>2</m> and the second equation by <m>-3</m>.
                Doing this will eliminate both variables and leave you with <m>0=0</m>.
                This should mean that all points on the line are solutions.
                So the solution set is <m>\{(x,y)\mid 6x+30y=15\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="lnS">
              <p permid="GVW">
                Substitution is definitely easiest here.
                Substituting <m>y</m> from one equation into <m>y</m> in the other equation gives you <m>3x-2=7x+6</m>.
                Solve this and find then find <m>y</m> and you should get the solution to the system to be <m>(-2,-8)</m> if you want to solve it for practice.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <exercises permid="Aiv">
    <subexercises>
      <title>Solving Systems of Linear Equations by Graphing</title>
      <exercisegroup cols="3" permid="gpE">
        <introduction permid="XFM">
          <p permid="Abr">
            Use a graph to solve the system of equations.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise permid="DMV">
          <statement>
            <p permid="giA">
              <me>\left\{\begin{aligned}
              x+y\amp=0\\
              3x-y\amp=8
              \end{aligned}\right.</me>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="aeT">
            <image permid="Fve">
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \begin{axis}[xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                      ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                      xtick={-8,-6,...,8},
                      minor xtick={-9,-8,...,9},
                      ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                      minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                      ]
                    \addplot[firstcurve,domain = -10:10]{-x} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$x+y=0$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve,domain = -0.6:6]{3*x-8} node[pos=1,sloped,below left] {$3x-y=8$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(2,-2)};
                  \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p permid="FQD">
              The two lines intersect where <m>x=2</m> and <m>y=-2</m>,
              so the solution is the point <m>(2,-2)</m>.
              We write the solution set as <m>\{(2,-2)\}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
